## 2. GHOSTTY

### Overview
A modern GPU-accelerated terminal built with Zig by Mitchell Hashimoto (creator of Terraform/Vagrant), released as v1.0 in December 2024. Aims to balance speed, features, and native UI.

### Performance
- **GPU Rendering**: Yes (Metal on macOS, OpenGL on Linux)
- **Startup Time**: Fast (~150ms)
- **Frame Rate**: 500+ FPS capable
- **CPU Usage**: 6-8% idle, efficient under load
- **Scroll Performance**: Extremely smooth, superior to many competitors

### Key Features
- **Cross-platform**: macOS (native), Linux (GTK)
- **Native UI Integration**: 
  - macOS: Quicklook, Secure Input API, native tabs/splits
  - Linux: GTK single app process, primary clipboard support
- **100+ built-in themes** with real-time preview
- **Built-in inspector** (Ctrl+Shift+I, like browser DevTools)
- **Native tabs and splits** with seamless management
- **Shell integration**: Bash, Zsh, Fish, Elvish
- **Advanced rendering**: Ligatures, variable fonts, grapheme clustering
- **Xterm compatibility** with Kitty graphics protocol support
- **Real-time configuration reload**
- **Complex prompt redrawing** on window resize

### Technical Stack
- **Language**: Zig (modern systems language with C speed + Rust safety)
- **Rendering**: Metal (macOS) / OpenGL (Linux)
- **Architecture**: Single-file configuration, no plugins needed

### Limitations
- Relatively new (v1 just released)
- Fewer third-party extensions than mature alternatives
- macOS-first development (though Linux support strong)
- Feature set still evolving

### Use Cases
- Developers wanting balance of speed and features
- macOS users seeking native integration
- Performance-conscious users who want built-in tabs/splits
- Developers who prefer configured-over-scripted approach
- Those wanting modern features without bloat

### Community & Support
- Active development post-v1 release
- Growing ecosystem
- Good documentation
- Design philosophy well-documented on ghostty.org

