## 4. iTERM2

### Overview
The most feature-rich macOS terminal emulator, long-standing industry standard for macOS users.

### Performance
- **GPU Rendering**: Yes (can be disabled on battery)
- **CPU Usage**: 10-20% (higher than modern alternatives)
- **Startup Time**: Reasonable (~500ms)
- **Scrolling**: Good with GPU enabled, poor with GPU disabled
- **Memory**: Moderate (depends on session count)

### Key Features
- **macOS Native**: Built with native Objective-C, tight OS integration
- **Advanced Session Management**:
  - Split panes (vertical/horizontal)
  - Tabbed sessions with thumbnails
  - Window grouping
- **Hotkey Window**: Global hotkey to bring iTerm2 to foreground
- **Instant Replay**: Rewind and view terminal history in real-time
- **Search & Autocomplete**: Powerful search across output
- **Paste History**: Access to recent paste buffer
- **Comprehensive Customization**: Profiles, keymaps, appearance
- **256+ Color Support**: True color support
- **Mouse Support**: Full mouse integration
- **Shell Integration**: Works with all shells

### Limitations
- **macOS-only**: Not cross-platform
- **Performance**: Slower than modern GPU-accelerated alternatives
- **Feature Bloat**: Complex interface, steep learning curve
- **Resource Usage**: Higher than minimalist terminals
- **Update Frequency**: Active but older codebase

### Advanced Features
- Deep customization of every aspect
- Advanced profile management with variables
- Semantic history tracking
- Command-line configuration possible

### Use Cases
- macOS exclusive users
- Users needing advanced session management
- Teams standardized on iTerm2
- Developers wanting feature richness
- Those comfortable with complexity for power

### Community
- Large user base
- Excellent documentation
- Active development continues

