## 6. TABBY

### Overview
An Electron-based terminal emulator emphasizing feature richness and modern UI, with support for SSH, Serial, and local shells.

### Performance
- **Framework**: Electron (TypeScript)
- **Startup Time**: Slow (splash screen, 2-3 seconds)
- **CPU/Memory**: High (Electron overhead)
- **UI Responsiveness**: Sluggish with animations enabled
- **Actual Terminal Emulation**: Acceptable once running

### Key Features
- **Integrated SSH Client**: Full SSH connection management
- **Multi-Protocol Support**: 
  - SSH/Telnet
  - Serial connections
  - Local shells (Bash, PowerShell, etc.)
- **Session Management**:
  - Session profiles with saved settings
  - SFTP file transfer integration
  - Z-modem support
- **UI Features**:
  - Tabbed interface with rich customization
  - Split panes
  - Status bar
  - Theme/color scheme library (25+)
- **Plugin System**: Extensible architecture
- **Cross-Platform**: Windows, macOS, Linux
- **CSS Customization**: Style UI with CSS
- **Full Unicode**: Double-width character support

### Technical Stack
- **Language**: TypeScript
- **Framework**: Electron
- **UI**: Complex component hierarchy

### Limitations
- **Performance**: Slow startup and animations
- **Resource Heavy**: Electron overhead significant
- **Animations**: Default animations make UI feel sluggish (can disable)
- **Loading Screen**: Undesirable startup behavior
- **Theme Limitations**: Not all theme colors apply completely
- **Complexity**: Feature bloat vs simplicity tradeoff

### Use Cases
- Cross-platform SSH management
- Development teams needing comprehensive features
- Serial console users
- Users prioritizing feature count over speed
- Those who disable animations for acceptable performance

### Community
- 40k+ GitHub stars
- Active development
- Good documentation
- Growing ecosystem

