## 9. WEZTERM

### Overview
A GPU-accelerated terminal emulator written in Rust, notable for powerful Lua-based configuration and excellent feature/performance balance.

### Performance
- **Language**: Rust
- **GPU Rendering**: Yes (OpenGL)
- **CPU Usage**: Efficient (Rust optimization)
- **Startup Time**: Fast
- **Scrolling**: Smooth and responsive
- **Throughput**: Competitive with other GPU-accelerated options

### Key Features
- **Lua Configuration**:
  - Full Lua 5.4 scripting for configuration
  - Programmable appearance and behavior
  - Event-driven architecture
  - Powerful customization comparable to Neovim
  - Consistent with editor configuration (Neovim + WezTerm combo)
- **Window/Tab Management**:
  - Native tabs and splits
  - Window multiplexing (built-in, like tmux)
  - Workspace navigation
  - Dynamic window creation via Lua
- **Advanced Features**:
  - Custom hyperlink highlighting rules
  - Searchable scrollback
  - Image support (Kitty Image Protocol)
  - Ligature support
  - Status bar customization
  - Modal keybindings and leader keys
  - Smart split management
- **Cross-Platform**: Windows, macOS, Linux
- **Shell Integration**: All major shells supported

### Configuration Philosophy
- Text-based configuration (Lua) in dotfiles
- Portable across machines
- No GUI configuration needed
- Event system (update-status, window-focus, etc.)
- Utility functions for system state access

### Limitations
- **Lua Learning Curve**: Configuration more complex than TOML
- **Inconsistent Performance**: Some users report variable performance
- **Windows Support**: Less polished than macOS/Linux
- **Ecosystem**: Smaller than iTerm2

### Advanced Capabilities
- **Status Bar**: Real-time system information display
- **Event Handlers**: Custom callbacks for terminal events
- **Terminal State Access**: Query mouse position, window state, etc.
- **File System Access**: Full Lua filesystem capabilities
- **Network Capabilities**: Can make HTTP requests from config

### Use Cases
- Developers comfortable with Lua scripting
- Neovim users (Lua configuration consistency)
- Power users wanting deep customization
- Cross-platform users needing dotfile portability
- Infrastructure professionals

### Community
- Strong user base among infrastructure/DevOps
- Active development
- Good documentation
- Growing Lua config examples

